<%
  // ----- About-modal data: full story + timeline -----
  const STORY = [
    {
      paragraph: `I'm <strong>Debarghya Sengupta</strong> — a <strong>final-year Computer Science engineering student</strong> at GNIT, Kolkata, and an engineer who doesn't just write code, I architect it. Clean APIs, efficient data flows, systems that hold under pressure. If there's a bug, an inconsistency, or a rough edge anywhere in the stack, it doesn't stay that way for long. <strong>I find it. I own it. I fix it — properly.</strong>`,
    },
    {
      paragraph: `My sweet spot lives where complexity meets precision: <em>RAG pipelines</em>, <em>CI/CD workflows</em>, and cloud infrastructure that doesn't flinch at scale. The kind of work where cutting corners isn't a shortcut — it's a liability.`,
    },
    {
      paragraph: `None of this came from nowhere. I started in 2023 at <strong>GNIT, Kolkata</strong> with my first lines of Java, Python and C — equal parts terrifying and thrilling. By 2024 I was shipping scrappy full-stack things in React, Node and Express. Most of them broke in interesting ways. Fixing them taught me more than ten tutorials ever could — that shipping imperfect work and learning in public is the only honest path forward.`,
    },
    {
      paragraph: `2025 was the year of leadership and credentials. I became <strong>Cloud Computing Lead</strong> at the Microsoft Student Ambassador GNIT Chapter and <strong>Co-Head of Mahakash Club</strong>, our space and aerospace community. Cloud certifications from Oracle (OCI Developer Professional, Generative AI Professional, AI Autonomous Database) and Microsoft Azure followed. <em>MediHub</em> taught me how dense healthcare workflows really are; <em>PotatoScan</em> taught me that AI quietly transforms agriculture when you keep the experience simple.`,
    },
    {
      paragraph: `This year — 2026 — I'm focused on <strong>AI engineering done right</strong>. <em>Nyatik Nayan</em> and <em>Fin-Eye</em> are my answers to two questions I keep asking: can AI catch retail fraud the moment it happens, and can it actually answer questions about dense financial documents without making things up? The only flaw you'll find in my code? <strong>I aimed for perfection and got too close to stop.</strong>`,
    },
  ];

  const TIMELINE = [
    {
      year: "2026",
      items: [
        "Building Nyatik Nayan (AI fraud detection) and Fin-Eye (RAG for financial docs).",
        "Leading Cloud Computing as MSA GNIT — workshops, Azure deep-dives, mentoring juniors.",
        "Going deeper on Java DSA — daily problems, building intuition for trees and graphs next.",
      ],
    },
    {
      year: "2025",
      items: [
        "Became Co-Head of Mahakash Club; ran our biggest space-awareness meet yet.",
        "Earned Oracle OCI Developer Professional, Oracle Generative AI Professional and OCI AI Autonomous Database certifications.",
        "Got the Microsoft Azure management foundation cert and the Zscaler Cybersecurity Fundamentals.",
        "Shipped MediHub (digital prescriptions) and PotatoScan (97% disease classification).",
      ],
    },
    {
      year: "2024",
      items: [
        "Built my first real full-stack projects with React, Node and Express.",
        "Designed and shipped the Mahakash Club website — my first deployed site that wasn't just for me.",
        "Wrote the first iteration of this portfolio. Hated it the next week. Started planning version two.",
      ],
    },
    {
      year: "2023",
      items: [
        "Entered GNIT for Computer Science Engineering.",
        "Wrote my first real programs in Java, Python and C — figured out the difference between code that runs and code that's understood.",
        "Decided I wanted to spend a long time figuring out how technology actually works.",
      ],
    },
  ];
%>
<div class="about-modal" id="about-modal" role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="about-modal-title" aria-hidden="true">
  <div class="about-modal-panel" role="document">
    <button class="about-modal-close" type="button" data-close-about aria-label="Close full story">
      <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
        <line x1="18" y1="6" x2="6" y2="18" />
        <line x1="6" y1="6" x2="18" y2="18" />
      </svg>
    </button>

    <header class="about-modal-head">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">// the whole story</span>
      <h2 id="about-modal-title" class="section-heading">The Story So Far</h2>
      <p class="section-subhead">
        From manifesto to milestones. The work, the wins, the wreckage.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="about-modal-body">
      <div class="story-grid">
        <div class="story-text">
          <% STORY.forEach(s => { %>
            <p><%- s.paragraph %></p>
          <% }) %>

          <div class="off-topic-wrap">
            <button type="button" class="btn-pill" data-toggle-offtopic aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="about-offtopic">
              <span data-offtopic-show>A little off-topic 👀</span>
              <span data-offtopic-hide hidden>Hide the off-topic stuff 🙈</span>
            </button>
            <div class="off-topic-content" id="about-offtopic" hidden>
              <p>
                When the editor closes, three things hold my attention: <strong>F1</strong>,
                <strong>cricket</strong>, and a good novel. F1 because every millisecond is
                engineered — the same precision I chase in code. Cricket because patience
                and pattern recognition decide it more than raw power. Books because the
                best stories and the best systems follow the same rule: every detail earns
                its place, or it gets cut.
              </p>
              <p>
                On the bedside stack: <em class="book-title">Hamlet</em> and
                <em class="book-title">Macbeth</em> by William Shakespeare, and
                <em class="book-title">The Fault in Our Stars</em> by John Green.
                Shakespeare for the structural discipline that holds a tragedy together
                line by line — the same discipline that holds a system together under load.
                Green for the quieter reminder that even the most precisely engineered
                things still have to hold a heart.
              </p>
              <p>
                I also read <strong>history</strong> for the same reason I read source code:
                every architecture and artifact we use today inherits from something older.
                Spend time with the past and the present stops feeling arbitrary — you start
                seeing why systems are the shape they are.
              </p>
              <p>
                Beyond that? <em>I don't believe in extravagance.</em> Less, but better.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <aside class="story-timeline">
          <h3 class="timeline-title">// the evolution</h3>
          <div class="timeline-list">
            <% TIMELINE.forEach(yr => { %>
              <div class="timeline-year">
                <span class="year-label"><%= yr.year %></span>
                <ul class="year-items">
                  <% yr.items.forEach(item => { %>
                    <li><%= item %></li>
                  <% }) %>
                </ul>
              </div>
            <% }) %>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
